column41: 1.	The current scan demonstrates several interval changes since the prior study which are difficult to unify on metabolic grounds.  2.	Extensive new avid right axillary nodes are highly suspicious of metastatic progression, with disease extending to the axillary apex / subpectoral region and right lateral chest wall.  Elliptical hypodensity in the surgical bed is likely attributable to a residual post-surgical collection.  3.	Interval increase in volume of avid bilateral pulmonary nodules with generalised parenchymal nodularity; these are indeterminate and difficult to differentiate between malignant (melanoma vs. thyroid) and benign (immune-related) aetiologies. Mild heterogeneous bilateral pleural uptake (R>L) is favoured to be inflammatory in nature.  4.	Symmetrical mediastinal/hilar nodes and upper abdominal nodal cluster raises the possibility of a granulomatous process, with nodal metastases a possible differential. Diffuse splenic uptake is likely reactive.  5.	Diffuse marrow uptake is likely reactive; the foci of relative prominence are less specific, and the possibility of osseous metastasis cannot be excluded.  6.	CT chest suggested to further characterise the lung changes, and early FDG-PET/CT follow up could potentially help to clarify current findings
